### File Structure
```
RestaurantReservation/
│
├── app.py
├── templates/
│   ├── dashboard.html
│   ├── menu.html
│   ├── dish_details.html
│   ├── make_reservation.html
│   ├── my_reservations.html
│   ├── waitlist.html
│   ├── my_reviews.html
│   ├── write_review.html
│   └── profile.html
│
├── static/
│   ├── css/
│   │   └── styles.css
│   ├── js/
│   │   └── scripts.js
│   └── images/
│       └── (dish images and other assets)
│
└── data/
    ├── users.txt
    ├── menu.txt
    ├── reservations.txt
    ├── waitlist.txt
    └── reviews.txt
```

### File Descriptions
```
app.py
- The main backend Python file implementing the web application using a web framework (e.g., Flask).
- Handles routing for all nine pages, data reading/writing to local text files in the 'data' directory.
- Implements business logic for reservations, waitlist management, reviews, user profile updates, and menu browsing.
- Manages session or user state to display personalized content such as username and user-specific data.

templates/
- Contains HTML template files for each of the nine pages defined in the requirements.
- Each template corresponds to a page and includes the specified elements with their IDs for frontend interaction.
- Templates use templating syntax to dynamically render data from the backend (e.g., user info, menu items, reservations).

static/
- Contains static assets such as CSS stylesheets, JavaScript files, and images.
- css/styles.css: Styles for consistent UI design across all pages.
- js/scripts.js: JavaScript for client-side interactivity, button actions, and page navigation.
- images/: Stores dish images and other graphical assets referenced in the menu and dish details pages.

data/
- Stores all application data in text files using the specified pipe-delimited format.
- users.txt: User account information.
- menu.txt: Restaurant menu items data.
- reservations.txt: Reservation records.
- waitlist.txt: Waitlist entries.
- reviews.txt: User reviews for dishes.

Notes:
- Backend logic is consolidated in a single Python file (app.py) since the application complexity is moderate.
- Separation of concerns is maintained by dividing frontend templates and static assets.
- The 'data' directory is dedicated to persistent storage as per requirements.
```
